The Democratic Alliance will be electing its leaders at the end of October. The Party’s federal Executive has resolved to holding a virtual elective conference on the 31st of October due to the covid-19 outbreak. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Democratic Alliance Federal Executive Chairperson Helen Zille is backing interim leader John Steenhuisen's comments about lockdown regulations. Steenhuisen says the lockdown cost more lives than it has saved. Zille says the regulations are unconstitutional and irrational. The party is taking the government to court over the lockdown regulations. READ: ANC Western Cape wants province to revert to Level 5 lockdown “There were three issues that we raised as being irrational, one was e-commerce, the second was the curfew which is a completely unconstitutional restriction on peoples lives, and the last one is the exercise window. The second case is focused on whether or not the disaster management act as a whole is constitutional and we say it isn’t, as the group of the executive is not accountable to anyone…we headed to the constitutional court to resolve that question”, said Zille. Meanwhile, the party has resolved to hold a virtual gathering of its elective conference at the end of October. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.